<br>
Anyhoo, it's a fake RPC Termination (Lovsan) window. Really well done too - looks just like the actual XP popup. If you've never dealt with the worm before, even with the a flashing &quot;FIX DETECTED, CLICK HERE TO UPDATE&quot; bit of text at the bottom it's pretty convincing. Clicking the flashing text results in a full-screen mousetrap ad for some random antivirus program. Closing that ad results in a cascade of popups for everything from tiny video cameras to mortgage services.<br>
<br>
I was entertained.<br>
<br>
I'll admit to clicking Start/Run on my way to opening a cmd window and abort the shutdown when it occured to me that I wasn't even running WinXP since I was at work, which is also when I noticed the flashing text on the alert.<br>
<br>
So, the upshot of this rambling diatribe is that I'm continually appalled at how insulting and devious advertisers are willing to get. There are a lot of people that own both computers and credit cards that would fall for something like this.<br>
<br>
Are ads like this a case for or against ye olde caveat emptor? Arguments like &quot;just get a popup stopper&quot; are bullshit here because the people most likely to fall for these types of ads are also highly unlikely to have any kind of popup prevention. While it's just faking an error, Joe User wouldn't know that. To me it's akin to a billboard for a windshield repair service that shoots rocks at passing cars.<br>
<br>
